'''''What's The Story?''''' was an exclusive feature on the ''Star Wars'' fan club website, [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club|''Star Wars'' Hyperspace]]. It gave Hyperspace members a chance to leave their mark on the ''Star Wars'' [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] by allowing them to provide the backstory for certain aspects of the saga, usually obscure background characters or vehicles from the films.

Winning entries became official ''Star Wars'' lore: published in the [[Databank (original)|Databank]] and added to the [[Holocron continuity database]]. This feature was launched [[June 24]], [[2005]] and concluded on [[January 4]], [[2008]], as first hinted by [[Pablo Hidalgo]] of [[Lucas Online]].<ref>{{Blog|lucasonline|64|What Is (And Isn't) Hyperspace?}}</ref><ref>{{WordPress|subdomain=starwarsblog|url=2007/05/27/webstrip-chatter-at-celebration-iv/#more-57|name=The Official Star Wars Blog|text=Webstrip Chatter at Celebration IV|author=Pablo Hidalgo|date=2007-06-27|archivedate=20200323053929}}</ref> The feature began with the backstory for [[Tannon Praji/Legends|Tannon Praji]], a character from the (then) recently released [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']], and, somewhat appropriately, the final entry was [[Bane Malar/Legends|Bane Malar]], a character from [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']], chronologically the (then) final Star Wars film.

In [[October]] 2008, new stories from ''What's The Story?'' authors began to be published on Hyperspace. As of [[March]] [[2010]], [[Edward M. Erdelac]], [[Nathan O'Keefe]], [[Adrick Tolliver]], [[James McFadden]], [[Gregory Walker]], and [[John Hazlett]] have authored Hyperspace articles.

==The process==
The submission form was regularly updated presenting a new subject for fans to write about, originally weekly, then in a fortnightly period and finally on the first Friday of every month. Entries were be based on the information and criteria given, and all had to be under 2000 characters in length. Every submission received was read by a panel of judges, with the best marked as finalists. [[Pablo Hidalgo]] then selected the winning entry, or merged several entries and edited them into the final product. The Databank was updated with five or six winners at a time or, sometimes, individually.

